      "title": "display: flex-grid v0.5",
      "pubDate": "2020-02-09 05:47:56",
      "link": "https://medium.com/@cakehole/micro-blog-ive-been-struggling-with-getting-elements-to-be-where-i-want-them-in-an-app-i-m-47303c8de83b?source=rss-4800652ebeb2------2",
      "guid": "https://medium.com/p/47303c8de83b",
      "author": "Kyle Cole",
      "thumbnail": "https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/1*RTM5nUISCNJbl_yOZTO7WQ.png",
      "description": "\n<p><strong>Micro Blog:</strong> Iâ€™ve been struggling with getting elements to be where I want them in an app Iâ€™m currently working on (more on that later). It works on mobile. but not desktop. I fix one, and the other breaks. Everything I google brings me back to CSS grid andÂ flexbox.</p>\n<p>Thatâ€™s great, but, <em>Iâ€™m new to this and I donâ€™t fully understand the core concepts behind grid and flexbox; the differences between them; and when to use which.</em> Iâ€™ve read several articles and watched a few tutorials now, but none really clarified my painÂ points.</p>\n<figure><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/1*RTM5nUISCNJbl_yOZTO7WQ.png\"><figcaption>Grids, amirite?</figcaption></figure><p>I finally found these tutorials from <a href=\"https://link.medium.com/LcXiMJdJV3\">Traversy Media</a> that really break it down in a way that worked for meâ€Šâ€”â€Šdirect and to the point, but assumes you know nothing (thatâ€™s a goodÂ thing).</p>\n<p>So, if youâ€™re struggling with how to position your elements while styling your apps, Iâ€™d highly recommend you take some time to watch these two tutorials to understand the basics, how to build off them, and why they work that way (he also has a wicked BostonÂ accent).</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jV8B24rSN5o\">grid (27Â min)</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JJSoEo8JSnc\">flexbawx (20Â min)</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Before attempting any major CSS refactors, always create a new branch on your repo: <em>git checkout -b css-grid-flexbox</em></p>\n<p><strong>I guarantee youâ€™ll breakÂ stuff.</strong></p>\n<p>I need a little more practice before I can share best practices with you; but trial and error is one of my specialties so Iâ€™ll report backÂ soon.</p>\n<p>cakehole out.</p>\n<img src=\"https://medium.com/_/stat?event=post.clientViewed&amp;referrerSource=full_rss&amp;postId=47303c8de83b\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" alt=\"\">\n",
      "content": "\n<p><strong>Micro Blog:</strong> Iâ€™ve been struggling with getting elements to be where I want them in an app Iâ€™m currently working on (more on that later). It works on mobile. but not desktop. I fix one, and the other breaks. Everything I google brings me back to CSS grid andÂ flexbox.</p>\n<p>Thatâ€™s great, but, <em>Iâ€™m new to this and I donâ€™t fully understand the core concepts behind grid and flexbox; the differences between them; and when to use which.</em> Iâ€™ve read several articles and watched a few tutorials now, but none really clarified my painÂ points.</p>\n<figure><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1024/1*RTM5nUISCNJbl_yOZTO7WQ.png\"><figcaption>Grids, amirite?</figcaption></figure><p>I finally found these tutorials from <a href=\"https://link.medium.com/LcXiMJdJV3\">Traversy Media</a> that really break it down in a way that worked for meâ€Šâ€”â€Šdirect and to the point, but assumes you know nothing (thatâ€™s a goodÂ thing).</p>\n<p>So, if youâ€™re struggling with how to position your elements while styling your apps, Iâ€™d highly recommend you take some time to watch these two tutorials to understand the basics, how to build off them, and why they work that way (he also has a wicked BostonÂ accent).</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jV8B24rSN5o\">grid (27Â min)</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JJSoEo8JSnc\">flexbawx (20Â min)</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Before attempting any major CSS refactors, always create a new branch on your repo: <em>git checkout -b css-grid-flexbox</em></p>\n<p><strong>I guarantee youâ€™ll breakÂ stuff.</strong></p>\n<p>I need a little more practice before I can share best practices with you; but trial and error is one of my specialties so Iâ€™ll report backÂ soon.</p>\n<p>cakehole out.</p>\n<img src=\"https://medium.com/_/stat?event=post.clientViewed&amp;referrerSource=full_rss&amp;postId=47303c8de83b\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" alt=\"\">\n",
